comments.comment_body:
We have our first confession in the trial and it is Alan Dershowitz acknowledging that his is a fringe interpretation of the Constitution in contrast to the consensus of the majority of constitutional scholars. He writes in a recent letter to the Times;

"While it is true that most other constitutional scholars believe that impeachment can be based on completely noncriminal type behavior, such as abuse of power, my independent research conducted over the past two years has led me to the opposite conclusion..."

No attorney worth their salt in a regular court trial would call forth this man as their expert witness...unless they had no other choice and were desperate to provide one to fit their narrative.

I am so happy not to be paying tuition to South Texas College of Law where I might be instructed by Prof. Blackman.

Here are the felonies committed by Trump et. al. in their Ukraine scheme:

Bribery - withholding the funds to Ukraine unless Zelenskyy pays with an announcement of an investigation against Biden;

Wire Fraud - using the Oval Office phone to commit the crime;

Conspiracy to commit bribery - using Giuliani, Pence, Mulvaney, Pompeo, Perry, Sondland, Parnas et. al. to further the crime;

Violation of Foreign Corrupt Practices Act - soliciting a bribe or extorting a foreign official, or attempting illegally to influence their actions;

Conspiracy to violate the above Act;

Violation of Congressional & Budget Approp. Act of 1974 - withholding funds appropriated lawfully by Congress;

Conspiracy to violate the above Act;

Obstruction of Justice/Congress - thwarting the investigation by withholding evidence and witnesses illegally (don't try to argue executive privilege; it doesn't apply to protect criminal acts);

Violation of campaign finance law - with Ukraine and previously, with the hush money paid to 2 women; Trump was named as a co-conspirator in the case which sent Michael Cohen to prison;

Conspiracy to violate the above act;

Violation of the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO). The law Giuliani used in the 1980s to prosecute the Mafia.

Your examples cite US-sited incidents; you ignore laws meant to police dealings with foreigners.

There are several fundamental problems with this OpEd.  So fundamental, in fact, that I'm genuinely shocked and disappointed that the author happens to be a constitutional law professor.  The primary shortcoming here is that Mr. Blackman confoundingly conflates a bland notion of "policy" with what Trump actually did.  Trump illegally1 and secretly withheld desperately needed and congressionally appropriated TAXPAYER funds from Ukraine so they'd announce (specifically on CNN) an investigation into the Bidens (and, of course, worked to cover all this up and obstruct congressional investigation of the same).  The aim was to create enough smoke that some folks might think there was there there.  And that would help Trump personally, which plainly was his SOLE aim.  That's not policy - that's extortion. And if it helped Trump get reelected?  Oh, he'd most certainly get more "money and property."  He's got emoluments running amok!  

And these examples from the Lincoln and LBJ presidencies?  This is some soggy oatmeal, professor.  Lincoln - the commander in chief - encouraged his soldiers to exercise a sacred civic duty.  LBJ merely filled a cabinet vacancy, as is his constitutional duty and privilege.  Neither of these acts comes close to amounting to the abject and criminal shakedown attempted by Trump.  

